	=09
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-keep-scrolling-for-a-quick-video-gui=
de-on-making-a-yeast-starter">Keep scrolling for a quick video guide on mak=
ing a yeast starter!</h3>



<p>Sure, homebrewers make the wort, but it=E2=80=99s yeast that makes the b=
eer. The process of converting wort into beer is a labor-intensive&nbsp;tas=
k for yeast, and it&nbsp;deserves all the help it&nbsp;can get to conduct a=
 quick but clean fermentation. One of the best ways to ensure yeast is&nbsp=
;empowered for the best fermentation is by creating a yeast starter.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-when-to-make-a-yeast-starter">When T=
o Make a Yeast Starter</h2>



<p>A&nbsp;standard package of liquid yeast typically contains about 100 bil=
lion viable yeast cells. Sounds like a lot, right? Well, that=E2=80=99s act=
ually only&nbsp;enough yeast for a 5-gallon batch of 1.048 original gravity=
 homebrew. As volumes, gravity or both increase, more yeast is&nbsp;needed.=
 On top of that, the number of viable yeast cells in a package decreases ov=
ertime.</p>



<p>So, if you are planning on brewing larger volumes, higher gravities or u=
sing older yeast packets, it=E2=80=99s wise to pursue a yeast starter to en=
sure you have enough healthy brewer=E2=80=99s yeast to get conduct quality =
fermentation.</p>



<p>Dry yeast doesn=E2=80=99t need a starter. Simply take the appropriate st=
eps to <a href=3D"https://homebrewersassociation.org/how-to-brew/rehydratin=
g-dry-yeast/">rehydrate dry yeast</a> prior to pitching.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-equipment-needed-for-yeast-starter">=
Equipment Needed for Yeast Starter</h2>



<p>When making a yeast starter, you=E2=80=99re&nbsp;essentially boiling and=
 fermenting a mini-batch of beer. First you=E2=80=99ll need a vessel large =
enough to hold the volume of the starter and something to cover the top, li=
ke foil or a stopper. The vessel can simply be a jar or plastic bottle, but=
 Erlenmeyer flasks that can withstand direct heat are a popular choice sinc=
e the entire boiling and fermentation process can be done in one&nbsp;vesse=
l. If not using a flask, you=E2=80=99ll need a pot to boil a small quantity=
 of wort. Other than that, you=E2=80=99ll need some water, dry malt extract=
 and sanitizer.</p>



<p>A stir plate, which can&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://homebrewersassociation.o=
rg/pimp-my-system/homebrew-diy-making-a-stir-plate/">easily be made at home=
</a>, is highly recommended to continually add oxygen to the starter, which=
 is crucial in growing the yeast cell population in a starter. If a stir pl=
ate is not available, simply giving the vessel a shake every now and again =
is better than not adding oxygen at all.</p>






<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-establishing-nbsp-ideal-yeast-cell-c=
ount">Establishing&nbsp;Ideal Yeast Cell Count</h2>



<p>It is important to have a target number of viable yeast cells when formu=
lating a starter. This is determined by the beer batch=E2=80=99s volume in =
relation to the original gravity. Generally speaking, an ale requires&nbsp;=
0.75&nbsp;million viable yeast cells for every milliliter of wort per every=
 degree plato, while lagers require 1.5 million viable yeast cells for ever=
y milliliter of wort per degree plato. So, for example, a 5-gallon batch of=
 1.064 ale wort would require about 227 billion viable yeast cells:</p>



<p class=3D"has-text-align-center"><strong>(0.75 million viable yeast cells=
) x (18925 mL of wort) x (16=C2=B0 Plato) =3D ~227 billion yeast cells</str=
ong></p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-determining-gravity-temperature-amp-=
volume-for-a-starter">Determining Gravity, Temperature &amp; Volume for a S=
tarter</h2>



<p><strong>Gravity:&nbsp;</strong>Aim to have the gravity in the 1.030-1.04=
0 range, which will promote healthy growth without introducing too much unn=
eeded stress.</p>



<p><strong>Temperature:&nbsp;</strong>In general, aim to keep yeast starter=
s around 72=C2=B0F (22=C2=B0C), with ales being able to be a few degrees wa=
rmer and lagers a few degrees cooler.</p>



<p><strong>Volume:&nbsp;</strong>Determining volume can be a very involved =
process. The volume of the starter in relation to the number of viable yeas=
t cells added, termed the inoculation rate, will determine the growth poten=
tial for the yeast starter.</p><div id=3D"div-gpt-ad-AHA_Index-ROS-2" class=
=3D"ad ad-inline"></div>



<p>For example, 200 billion yeast cells added to a 2 liter starter will hav=
e significantly less overall growth than adding 100 billion yeast cells to =
the same volume. There are charts, like the one in <a href=3D"https://www.b=
rewerspublications.com/products/yeast-the-practical-guide-to-beer-fermentat=
ion?_pos=3D1&amp;_sid=3D497a68be6&amp;_ss=3Dr" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener noreferrer"><em>Yeast: A Practical Guide to Beer Fermentation</em></a=
>, that can help make informed decisions. However, you may prefer to use a =
program like the <a href=3D"http://www.mrmalty.com/calc/calc.html" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Mr. Malty Pitch Rate Calculator</a>=
, which not only helps determine volume, but also the target number of yeas=
t cells based on your beer=E2=80=99s volume and original gravity.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-=
embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class=3D"wp-bl=
ock-embed__wrapper" data-placeholder_class_index=3D"1" data-placeholder-ima=
ge=3D"https://homebrewersassociation.org/wp-content/uploads/complianz/place=
holders/youtubeMp9CnrOnVL8-maxresdefault.webp">
<div class=3D"fluid-width-video-wrapper" style=3D"padding-top: 56.2%;"><ifr=
ame data-placeholder-image=3D"https://homebrewersassociation.org/wp-content=
/uploads/complianz/placeholders/youtubeMp9CnrOnVL8-maxresdefault.webp" data=
-category=3D"marketing" data-service=3D"youtube" class=3D"cmplz-placeholder=
-element cmplz-video cmplz-processed cmplz-activated" data-cmplz-target=3D"=
src" data-src-cmplz=3D"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Mp9CnrOnVL8?feature=3D=
oembed" title=3D"How To Make A Yeast Starter" src=3D"cid:frame-82A88A770AC0=
5E40888F9B9FDE933099@mhtml.blink" frameborder=3D"0" allow=3D"accelerometer;=
 autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture;=
 web-share" referrerpolicy=3D"strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscr=
een=3D"" name=3D"fitvid0"></iframe></div>
</div></figure>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-the-steps-to-make-a-yeast-starter">T=
he Steps to Make a Yeast Starter</h2>



<p>Now, all that=E2=80=99s left is to actually make the starter! The follow=
ing are general instructions that can be applied to all sizes of starter:</=
p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Determine the appropriate starter volume to achieve the target number o=
f viable yeast cells for your beer.&nbsp;Remember, you can use an online ye=
ast calculator like the one linked above to quickly determine these variabl=
es.</li>



<li>Weigh out 1 gram of dry malt extract for every 10 milliliters of target=
 starter volume.</li>



<li>Add the dry malt extract to the vessel you will be boiling in.</li>



<li>Add enough water to the boil vessel (dry malt already added) to reach t=
he target starter volume.</li>



<li>Add about 1/4 teaspoon of yeast nutrient to the boil vessel. You can us=
e slight less for starters under 1-2 L and slightly more for ones larger.</=
li>



<li>Bring to a gentle boil for about 15 minutes. Keep the boil vessel cover=
ed to maintain as much of the volume as possible.</li>



<li>After 15 minutes, allow the wort to cool.</li>



<li>If needed, transfer the liquid to the vessel that will hold the starter=
.&nbsp;(Note: As with beer, anything that comes into contact with the start=
er wort post-boil should be properly clean and sanitized).</li>



<li>Pitch yeast into the chilled starter wort.</li>



<li>Use a stir plate or intermittent shaking to add vital oxygen to the sta=
rter.</li>



<li>Pitch into beer once ready!</li>
</ol>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-how-to-pitch-a-yeast-starter">How to=
 Pitch a Yeast Starter</h2>



<p>Starters are typically either pitched during high krausen or after activ=
e fermentation has subsided.</p>



<p>Pitching at high krausen, or at the height of the fermentation=E2=80=99s=
 activity, which typically is 12-18 hours after pitching the yeast into the=
 starter is the most convenient method. Simply pitch the entire contents of=
 the starter into the wort of your homebrew once it=E2=80=99s ready.</p>



<p>Be sure the temperature is within 5-15=C2=B0F of the wort=E2=80=99s temp=
erature when using this method. If it=E2=80=99s too hot or too cold, it can=
 shock the yeast and ultimately create problem fermentations.</p>



<p>Warm starters or starters with volumes more than 5% of the main batch vo=
lume need additional preparation. First, allow the fermentation to basicall=
y complete and then chill the starter by placing it in the fridge until it =
is near the temperature of the wort it is intended for. Decant the liquid a=
nd pitch&nbsp;only the yeast cake.</p><div id=3D"div-gpt-ad-AHA_Index-ROS-3=
" class=3D"ad ad-inline"></div>



<p>That=E2=80=99s it! You just pitched the perfect amount of yeast in your =
homebrew.</p>



